english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Celebrating the Birth of a Son
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring following the year that General Ha, the密直 of Jeolla Province, took his post at his garrison, his aide Park Won-bin spoke to me, saying: "General Ha's honored father remains robust and unafflicted, at the age of seventy-six. He has now fathered another son in our township. Prime Minister Ha himself composed a poem first to commemorate this occasion, and the cultured scholars of Jinju have all taken up the song. Do you know of this?"

    I reflected upon this matter. A virtuous gentleman of noble character accumulates abundant merit within himself, yet refrains from consuming its rewards. In this way, his descendants multiply and flourish, and worthy and wise persons emerge from his house. Through their service to rulers and establishment of the Way, they bring peace to the people, transforming a single family's fortune into the fortune of the realm. Therefore, when the ancients expressed their fondest wishes for a person, they always spoke of the prosperity of his descendants. The Book of Poetry states, "The filial son's virtue never ends," and again, "To the ages, we grant blessings and progeny." These are all manifestations of such abundant merit.

    General Ha's honored father does not pursue fame and glory. He has withdrawn into a life of modest simplicity, instructing his descendants and spreading refinement throughout his community. Does this not show one whose abundant merit, unexhausted, has been carefully cultivated?

    The General himself studied deeply to become a master scholar, competed in the civil examinations, and rose preeminently above all others. From his initial entry into office to his present rank among the highest ministers, serving in both central and provincial posts, he has maintained unwavering integrity through both fair and difficult times, never diminishing his reputation for virtue. Though this surely stems from the teachings of his household, is it not also Heaven's way of rewarding such profound moral excellence?

    Heaven's gracious and generous care toward the Ha family persists without ceasing. Late in life, Heaven granted him a worthy son, thus demonstrating that its bestowal of lineage shall continue without end. I am quite confident that the scholars of Jinju will not cease their songs with this one occasion. That the General has ascended to the seat of highest minister and enjoys wealth and honor—Heaven has bestowed these upon him in days past. Why should Heaven be miserly in what it grants hereafter?
  footnotes:
    - Milchik (密直) was a high official position in the Goryeo and early Joseon periods.
    - The references to the Book of Poetry (詩經) invoke classical Chinese precedents for celebrating virtue and filial piety as sources of familial and dynastic blessing.
    - Jinju (晉州) was an important administrative center in the Jeolla region during this period.
